---
import BaseLayout from '@/components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
import VerdictCardMock from '@/components/diagrams/VerdictCardMock.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How Moe Qadan works"
  description="The way I think about UX, frontend, design systems, AI-assisted prototyping, and platforms that already exist. Direct version: read the constraints, get the structure right, use AI where it earns its place."
  keywords={[
    'Moe Qadan',
    'design approach',
    'design engineering',
    'UX engineering',
    'AI-assisted design',
    'prompt engineering',
    'design systems',
    'product design process',
    'Claude Design',
    'Figma',
    'Cursor',
  ]}
>
  <div class="apr">
    <div class="apr__hero">
      <div class="container-site">
        <span class="apr__eyebrow">Approach</span>
        <h1 class="apr__title">How I work.</h1>
        <p class="apr__subtitle">
          The short version. The long version is the rest of this page.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container-site apr__body">
      {/* Lead — discursive, not symmetrical */}
      <section class="apr__section apr__section--lead" data-reveal>
        <p class="apr__lead">
          Most of what I'm hired to do is repair. A platform that grew
          without a system. A site that ranks well and converts badly.
          A frontend that looks fine in Chrome and falls apart on iOS
          15. AI tooling that demos beautifully and has nowhere to live
          in the codebase. Greenfield work happens, but it's the
          minority. The skill that matters more is reading what's
          already there before changing any of it.
        </p>

        <p class="apr__para">
          That's a long way of saying I'm a senior generalist. UX,
          frontend, design systems, content architecture, SEO,
          performance, accessibility, AI-assisted prototyping. Whichever
          subset the work needs, on whatever platform the company runs
          on. The skills sit in one head, so the tradeoffs between them
          get made in one head, which tends to ship faster and cleaner
          than handoff loops between three specialists.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="apr__rule" />

      {/* What I actually do, day to day */}
      <section class="apr__section" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="apr__h2">A normal week</h2>
        <p class="apr__para">
          Concretely, the recurring work in any given week looks
          something like this.
        </p>

        <ul class="apr__bullets">
          <li>Modify a Razor partial that's used in fifty places, knowing the typed ViewModel will surface every consumer that needs to update.</li>
          <li>Argue for a slower header hero against the "but the carousel is what marketing wants" reflex, and sequence the migration so the analytics taxonomy doesn't go dark.</li>
          <li>Open a hand-authored CSS file, find the spacing token that's almost right but not quite, decide whether to add a new token or stretch the existing one. Most of the time it's stretch.</li>
          <li>Write a prompt module for ChatOBD2 that lives in the system, not in a component. Version it. Budget it inside the 38,000-token system prompt assembly.</li>
          <li>Read a Figma file someone handed off. Notice the spacing they almost got right. Translate it into production at fidelity, while quietly fixing the spacing.</li>
          <li>Run Lighthouse, watch the LCP regress when a marketing team drops a hero image, find a workable compromise that keeps both groups happy.</li>
          <li>Ship something into production that nobody but me will notice. Watch the bug board not light up.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <hr class="apr__rule" />

      {/* AI in the work — concrete, not slogans */}
      <section class="apr__section" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="apr__h2">How AI actually fits in</h2>

        <p class="apr__para">
          Two places: in the products I ship, and in the way I build
          them.
        </p>

        <p class="apr__para">
          <strong>In the products.</strong> ChatOBD2 is the worked
          example. Vehicle data flows through six deterministic
          reasoning layers before any model call. The system prompt is
          composed per scan from a 38,000-token budget, with priority
          tiers that decide what stays in and what gets dropped if
          there's not enough room. Prompts live in a single module,
          keyed by verdict tier and code context, so a copy change is
          one file edit, not a hunt across the components that happen
          to render that text. Outputs are schema-bound, which means
          the rendering layer can stop apologizing for the model.
        </p>

        <div class="apr__art" data-reveal>
          <span class="apr__art-caption">ChatOBD2 verdict surface</span>
          <VerdictCardMock />
        </div>

        <p class="apr__para">
          <strong>In the build.</strong> Claude and Cursor handle code
          work. Either one. The choice is contextual, not by role.
          Figma stays for precision and design-system maintenance.
          Claude Design comes in for visual exploration when a frame is
          faster to reason about than markup. None of this is fancy.
          The codebase is the source of truth across all of them; the
          tools are interchangeable, the system isn't.
        </p>

        <p class="apr__para">
          What I don't do is treat AI as the product. The model is one
          stage in a structured pipeline; a human still owns every
          decision that ships. The point is repeatability, not novelty.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="apr__rule" />

      {/* What I bring to a team */}
      <section class="apr__section" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="apr__h2">What I'm best at on a team</h2>

        <ul class="apr__bullets">
          <li><strong>Owning the whole web experience for a team that doesn't have a department for it.</strong> One person carrying UX, the design system, the frontend, the content model, the SEO graph, and the perf budget. Most teams under-invest in this generalist; it's where I add the most.</li>
          <li><strong>Modernizing a platform that can't be rewritten.</strong> Long-running stacks have opinions. I read those first, plan around them, and ship in increments that don't require a flag day.</li>
          <li><strong>Building systems engineers actually use.</strong> Typed components. Tokens. Layout primitives. Real consumers from day one. No big-bang library that ships into a vacuum.</li>
          <li><strong>Sitting between design and engineering and unblocking both.</strong> I read intent, not just specs. Most production breakage lives in the gap a handoff doesn't see.</li>
          <li><strong>Prototyping with AI without losing taste.</strong> Faster from concept to shipped, without outsourcing judgment.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <hr class="apr__rule" />

      {/* Tools, plain */}
      <section class="apr__section" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="apr__h2">Tools I reach for</h2>
        <p class="apr__para">
          The default stack changes per project. The judgment about
          which tool to use for which job stays the same.
        </p>

        <ul class="apr__tools">
          <li>
            <span class="apr__tool-name">Claude</span>
            <span class="apr__tool-role">Code work and reasoning. The default for non-trivial refactors and anything that needs to think across more than one file.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="apr__tool-name">Cursor</span>
            <span class="apr__tool-role">Local iteration. Same code work as Claude, different interaction model. Whichever is faster on the task at hand.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="apr__tool-name">Figma</span>
            <span class="apr__tool-role">Precision design, component-system maintenance, handoff fidelity, and the occasional client review.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="apr__tool-name">Claude Design</span>
            <span class="apr__tool-role">Visual exploration when a frame is faster to think in than code. Output lands back in the codebase.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <hr class="apr__rule" />

      {/* Across the work */}
      <section class="apr__section" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="apr__h2">Across the work</h2>
        <p class="apr__para">
          Different companies, different stacks, the same question
          underneath: how do I move this surface from where it is to
          where it should be without breaking what's already running.
        </p>

        <div class="apr__work-grid">
          <figure class="apr__work-shot">
            <img
              src="/images/chatobd2/hero.webp"
              alt="ChatOBD2 marketing hero with phone mockup of a live diagnostic chat."
              width="1440"
              height="900"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>ChatOBD2.</strong> AI-native diagnostics, designed
              and engineered solo.
              <a href="/work/chatobd2">Case study</a>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="apr__work-shot">
            <img
              src="/images/magtek/homepage.webp"
              alt="MagTek homepage with metric story and team photography."
              width="1440"
              height="900"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>MagTek.</strong> Web experience across a multi-site
              platform on a long-running ASP.NET MVC stack.
              <a href="/work/magtek-platform">Case study</a>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="apr__work-shot">
            <img
              src="/images/sawa/hero.webp"
              alt="Sawa marketing hero with phone mockup of a matched restaurant card."
              width="1440"
              height="900"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Sawa.</strong> Marketing site for an iMessage-native
              group dining app.
              <a href="/work/sawa">Case study</a>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="apr__work-shot">
            <img
              src="/images/financial-platforms/chase.webp"
              alt="Chase homepage built on the InvestCloud framework."
              width="1440"
              height="900"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Advisor portals.</strong> Multi-tenant frontend
              across 50+ wealth and banking institutions at InvestCloud.
              <a href="/work/financial-platforms">Case study</a>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .apr__hero {
    padding-top: calc(60px + var(--space-10));
    padding-bottom: var(--space-10);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-10);
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .apr__hero {
      padding-top: calc(64px + var(--space-16));
      padding-bottom: var(--space-12);
      margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    }
  }

  .apr__eyebrow {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-text-subtle);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .apr__title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(40px, 9vw, 80px);
    font-weight: 400;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    line-height: 1.05;
    color: var(--color-text);
    max-width: 18ch;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }

  .apr__subtitle {
    font-size: clamp(15px, 1.5vw, 17px);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text-subtle);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .apr__body {
    padding-bottom: var(--space-16);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-12);
    max-width: 1080px;
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .apr__body {
      padding-bottom: var(--space-24);
      gap: var(--space-16);
    }
  }

  .apr__rule {
    border: none;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .apr__section {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-5);
  }

  .apr__section--lead {
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .apr__h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(24px, 3vw, 36px);
    font-weight: 400;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.15;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .apr__lead {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(20px, 2.4vw, 26px);
    font-weight: 400;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: var(--color-text);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .apr__para {
    font-size: clamp(15px, 1.5vw, 17px);
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    max-width: 64ch;
  }

  .apr__para strong {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .apr__bullets {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 66ch;
  }

  .apr__bullets li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 24px;
    font-size: clamp(15px, 1.5vw, 17px);
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .apr__bullets li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.7em;
    width: 12px;
    height: 1px;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .apr__bullets strong {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .apr__art {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  .apr__art-caption {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-text-subtle);
  }

  .apr__art :global(.verdict-mock__head) {
    display: none;
  }

  .apr__art :global(.verdict-mock) {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .apr__tools {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  @media (min-width: 720px) {
    .apr__tools {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-4);
    }
  }

  .apr__tools li {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 6px;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-elevated);
  }

  .apr__tool-name {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-text);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .apr__tool-role {
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }

  .apr__work-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-5);
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
  }

  @media (min-width: 720px) {
    .apr__work-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-6);
    }
  }

  .apr__work-shot {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .apr__work-shot img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .apr__work-shot figcaption {
    font-size: 13px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2px;
  }

  .apr__work-shot figcaption strong {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .apr__work-shot figcaption a {
    color: var(--color-text);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: var(--color-border);
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    font-size: 12px;
    transition: color 150ms, text-decoration-color 150ms;
  }

  .apr__work-shot figcaption a:hover {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration-color: var(--color-accent);
  }
</style>
